	id="Illu_OrientedVolume">
	<title>Oriented Volume - Illustration</title>
	<sub.page.body>
		<block>
			<para>To see the difference between &lsquo;volume&rsquo; and &lsquo;oriented volume&rsquo;, consider the picture below</para>
			<figure>
				<img src="ims/OrientedVolume.png"></img><!-- svg available -->
			</figure>
			<para>Here we have</para>
			<computation>
				<left>\Vol(\Vect{x},\Vect{y})</left>
				<center>=</center>
				<right>6</right>
				<left>\Vol(\Vect{u},\Vect{v})</left>
				<center>=</center>
				<right>6</right>
			</computation>
			<para>However, taking into account orientations, note that <latex>\omega(\Vect{x},\Vect{y})=+1</latex>, while <latex>\omega(\Vect{u},\Vect{v})=-1</latex>. Therefore</para>
			<computation>
				<left>\OriVol(\Vect{x},\Vect{y})</left>
				<center>=</center>
				<right>6</right>
				<left>\OriVol(\Vect{u},\Vect{v})</left>
				<center>=</center>
				<right>-6</right>
			</computation>
		</block>
	</sub.page.body>
</sub.page>